On to the Update:

TSMC Earnings
-------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-01-10/tsmc-qu=
arterly-sales-trail-estimates-as-global-chip-demand-wanes ) :

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. recorded its first quarterly revenue=
 miss in two years, signaling the global decline in electronics demand is s=
tarting to catch up with the chip giant. The shortfall suggests that even T=
SMC, with its technology and scale advantages, can=E2=80=99t escape a globa=
l slowdown in spending by consumers affected by rising interest rates and a=
ccelerating inflation. The world=E2=80=99s biggest contract manufacturer of=
 chips last year reduced its capital spending plans by about 10% to $36 bil=
lion and some analysts have warned it may further delay expenditure on expa=
nsion in 2023.

These numbers, particularly this quarter=E2=80=99s forecast of a 2.7% reven=
ue decline, were a tad worse than expected, but in the grand scheme of thin=
gs =E2=80=94 specifically, the way things usually go during semiconductor d=
ownturns =E2=80=94=C2=A0pretty good. The reason is because TSMC is actually=
 taking share. First, CEO C.C. Wei said on the company=E2=80=99s earnings c=
all ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4569491-taiwan-semiconductor-manufac=
turing-company-limited-tsm-q4-2022-earnings-call-transcript ) that while se=
miconductor industry growth ex-memory grew 10% last year, the foundry indus=
try increased 27%; that is basically a direct reference to the tumbling for=
tunes of Intel, by far the largest integrated device manufacturer (IDM). Mo=
reover, TSMC is increasing its share within the foundry business: Wei forec=
ast that in 2023 the semiconductor market ex-memory would decline 4%, the f=
oundry industry would decline 3%, while TSMC itself would grow slightly.

This is an excellent example of it being good to be the king: first, TSMC i=
s guaranteed business from companies that need to be on the bleeding edge, =
particularly smartphone providers and high-performance computing. Second, T=
SMC=E2=80=99s lead means that companies like AMD will continue to take shar=
e from Intel. Third, when and if TSMC capacity opens up, or decreases in pr=
ice, customers for other foundries are happy to jump over to TSMC.

That noted, TSMC=E2=80=99s earnings also offered an excellent example of ho=
w foundry margins are closely tied to utilization rates: TSMC=E2=80=99s gro=
ss margins this quarter are set to fall 720 basis points primarily due to l=
ower utilization. When most of the cost of a chip is set-in-stone depreciat=
ion costs spread across every chip produced, fewer chips produced mean plum=
meting margins. These numbers are still fine for TSMC; the more important t=
akeaway is considering the implications of this math for a company like Int=
el that is rapidly losing share.

Geographic Flexibility
----------------------

The most interesting part of the call were the repeated references to =E2=
=80=9Cgeographic flexibility=E2=80=9D as a part of TSMC=E2=80=99s value pro=
position. Chairman Mark Liu said:

TSMC is a service business, not in just pure production. The service depend=
s on the trust from the customers. So, in the past, our trust and service d=
epends on our technology leadership, manufacturing excellence, the lowest c=
ost, and quality. But recently, the geopolitical development is evolving ju=
st in front of us: 100% in one place cannot suffice our customers=E2=80=99 =
needs. Therefore, we started the overall global footprint planning.

Now of course, the cost will be higher. And I think our team has been focus=
ed on how do we do this at the same time, keep our minimum gross margin to =
be 53% and above. And that is the standard that we decide how the pace of o=
ur global expansion going to be, and there are other segments in terms of t=
he space, of course. The global expansion increased the value to our custom=
ers and the new geopolitical environment. And therefore, the pricing, how t=
he customer can shoulder the increased cost in terms of pricing. And of cou=
rse, geopolitically, the semiconductors in the U.S. and Japan are all new.

So, I believe we are working hard on how to reduce the cost by building up =
the semiconductor supply ecosystem in U.S. and Japan. And I think indeed, b=
oth governments are helping =E2=80=93 not just us, also rather other major =
companies to build a similar capacity in this place to reduce the costs. So=
, that is the general arrangement we are planning. There is no fixed rate. =
Of course, the government support will be another factor. And so that is, w=
e are cautiously step-by-step to make sure our shareholders=E2=80=99 value =
still be kept.

First off, that bit about TSMC being a services business is a point I have =
noted before, particularly in the context of Intel=E2=80=99s attempt to bui=
ld a foundry business. The challenge for the latter is not simply catching =
up to TSMC in terms of process, but also developing an entirely new compete=
ncy that is completely foreign to Intel: customer service (as opposed to ta=
ke-it-or-leave-it).

Secondly, this framing of TSMC=E2=80=99s geographic expansion certainly lin=
es up with my read on TSMC=E2=80=99s Arizona announcement last month, at le=
ast in part. I wrote in a Daily Update ( https://stratechery.com/2022/tsmc-=
in-arizona-arizona-challenges-realities-and-motivations/?access_token=3DeyJ=
