ubsidies that are unfortunately mostly going to the leading edge).

What is more important to the powers-that-be, though, is that President Bid=
en gets to make a big speech about a big dollar figure and Tim Cook gets to=
 talk about =E2=80=9CMade in America=E2=80=9D without having to discuss the=
 company=E2=80=99s continued dependence on China. TSMC will have to bear th=
e cost, but if that is the price of shoring up U.S. support for Taiwan, wel=
l, that is the best possible insurance policy the company could buy for its=
 operations that truly matter, which are intrinsically tied to Taiwan.

I think this is mostly right: if Apple and Nvidia and AMD want to say they =
have chips Made in America, well, TSMC is a customer service organization, =
and they will give their customers what they want (even if construction cos=
ts in the U.S. are 5x the Taiwan cost, as TSMC relayed on the call). At the=
 same time, Wei confirmed on the call that TSMC has no plans to build any p=
ackaging facilities in the U.S.: in other words, these U.S. chips will stil=
l have to be flown back to Taiwan to be packaged before they can be deliver=
ed to customers.

What I was wrong about was stating that TSMC will have to bear the cost; We=
i stated on the call: =E2=80=9COur pricing will remain strategic to reflect=
 our value, which also includes the value of geographic flexibility.=E2=80=
=9D In other words, if geographic flexibility is important to you, TSMC wil=
l provide it, and charge accordingly.

The 7nm Question
----------------

In the excerpt above I referenced TSMC taking a page out of Intel=E2=80=99s=
 playbook; what will be interesting is to what extent TSMC has to also foll=
ow Intel=E2=80=99s lead in terms of pricing generally.

TSMC was, for many years, behind the leading edge, so it had to price its c=
hips relatively low from the get-go; it made up for this by keeping fabs in=
 production years and years, churning out low-cost chips long past the poin=
t where the fab was fully depreciated. Intel, on the other hand, only kept =
fabs for the cutting edge (or at most a generation or two behind); they mad=
e this work by charging very high prices.

Of course that was then, and this is now; TSMC has long been moving more to=
wards the Intel side of the equation in terms of its pricing for the leadin=
g edge, and the cost of =E2=80=9Cgeographic flexibility=E2=80=9D is only go=
ing to add to that trend. Still, at the same time, TSMC would certainly pre=
fer to keep its old business model intact: it wants to keep the once-cuttin=
g edge fabs it built in use for many years to come.

This is where 7nm comes in. TSMC=E2=80=99s 7nm process was first introduced=
 in 2018, and first shipped in volume as the manufacturing process undergir=
ding the A12 processor in the iPhone XS; the A12 eventually shipped in not =
just the iPhone XS but also the XR, the 5th generation iPad Mini, the 3rd g=
eneration iPad Air, the 8th generation iPad, and the second generation Appl=
e TV 4k. All of those products are now discontinued. Now Apple, to be fair,=
 is the most committed to being on the cutting edge of anyone, but the tren=
d is clear: consumer electronics even now can never have fast-enough and ef=
ficient-enough chips; most things shipping today are on some variation of 5=
nm, and all new Apple chips will be 3nm (Apple is still shipping an iPad an=
d the Studio Display with the 7nm A13).

That leaves open the question as to who is going to use that 7nm capacity? =
Wei discussed this in his prepared remarks:

Next, let me talk about the N7-N6 demand outlook [ Note: N6 is, like N4 to =
N5, simply an evolution of the N7 process ]. Three months ago, we said our =
N7-N6 capacity utilization in first half =E2=80=9823 will not be as high as=
 it has been in the past 3 years due to end market weakness in smartphone a=
nd PCs and customer=E2=80=99s product schedule delay. Since then, the end m=
arket demand for smartphone and PCs has further weakened and the capacity u=
tilization of N7-N6 is lower than our expectation 3 months ago. We expect t=
his to persist through first half of 2023 as our semiconductor supply chain=
 inventory takes a few quarters to rebalance to a healthier level and we ex=
pect a mild pickup in our N7-N6 demand in second half 2013 than our prior e=
xpectation.

However, we continue to believe N7, N6 demand is more a cyclical issue rath=
er than structural. We are working closely with our customers to develop sp=
ecialty and differentiated technologies to drive additional wave of structu=
ral demand from consumer, RF, connectivity and other applications to backfi=
ll our N7, N6 capacity over the next several years. Thus, we are confident =
our 7-nanometer family will continue to be a large and long-lasting node fo=
r TSMC.

I think it is an open-question whether or not N7 demand will be back-filled=
 by speciality applications, and I=E2=80=99m not the only one; credit to Ch=
arles Shi from Needham & Company for asking the exact question I would have=
:

*I want to ask about specialty technology. Obviously, you expect specialty =
technology to backfill your 7-nanometer fabs. I think this may be a more co=
mmon knowledge inside the industry, but I recently spoke to some of your cu=
stomers who are more on the analog mixed signal side. A lot of them are, I =
mean driving volumes more from 28-nanometer and above, and they could tell =
me that the benefit of going to 14-nanometer, 16-nanometer for 7-nanometer =
is there, but it=E2=80=99s not large as in the past, moving node-to-node. A=
nd at the same time, the cost is much higher, and I look at your technology=
 roadmap, specialty technology roadmap, it does seems to me that the specia=
lty technology platforms are not as broad at the 7-nanometer if I compare w=
ith the 28-nanometer and above. I just want to get some insights from you. =
How do you think about the progression of specialty technology going forwar=
d, as it seems to me that it=E2=80=99s kind of slowing down a little bit mo=
re slowing a little bit down faster for the analog mixed signal customers?*

This is the exact right question to ask: if 7nm is much more expensive, and=
 the benefits much less for analog chips than cutting edge SoC chips, why i=
s there an expectation that that capacity will be utilized going forward? T=
his was Wei=E2=80=99s answer:

Charles, your observation is quite good. Actually, you are right. But then =
let me share with you a little bit more detail inside. Actually, you are ri=
ght, for the analog portion or mixed signal portion, we do not need to real=
ly move into 7-nanometer or more ones now. But as time goes by, now is more=
 and more computing functionality needed to be added into the product. Let =
me share with you that one thing like the WiFi, you need a really very high=
 speed to move to the next generation and also the RF. For those kind of th=
ings, you need a very high-performance of the computing together with low-p=
ower consumption. It is important. And if you want to get the lower power c=
onsumption, the only the leading-edge node can give you that kind of opport=
unities, all the footprint stays the same. Then if you want to have a highe=
r functionality with a lower power consumption, that=E2=80=99s where you ha=
ve to move into the 7-nanometer or more end node even with the analog produ=
ct.

This is right as far as it goes: 7nm is certainly more efficient than 28nm =
or 90nm or whatever node these chips are being made at; at the same time, w=
hen it comes to, say, a Wifi router, there is simply a lot more capacity fo=
r a relatively hot chip sucking power from an outlet than there is for a ch=
ip in a smartphone running on a battery, and the higher price for a more ef=
ficient node may not be worth it. It will be in some cases, for sure, but n=
ot all of them; the question of where that line will be drawn going forward=
 is going to have a big impact on TSMC=E2=80=99s profitability in the long-=
run.

